My main thesis about fraud is that it is very much defined by local social =
expectations. If you are playing poker and you bet like you have a big hand=
, trying to deceive people into folding, and it works and they fold and you=
 take their money, and then you flip over your cards and show that you have=
 nothing and say =E2=80=9Chahaha I was bluffing, suckers,=E2=80=9D they mig=
ht be annoyed with=C2=A0themselves, for folding, or even with you, for gloa=
ting, but they won=E2=80=99t accuse you of fraud. They won=E2=80=99t call t=
he police, or even stop playing with you. They are part of a social context=
 in which they expect their counterparties to try to deceive them, and in w=
hich they sometimes try to deceive their counterparties, and their reaction=
 to a bold and successful bluff will mostly be =E2=80=9Cwow, good one, you =
got me.=E2=80=9DThis is not true of most areas of life, but it is sort of t=
rue of some areas, and those areas tend to be where a lot of fraud cases co=
me from. In the bond market, if you are a trader at a bank and a customer c=
omes to you and says =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d like to buy XYZ bonds=E2=80=9D an=
d you say =E2=80=9CI=C2=A0have some, I paid 106 for them, I=E2=80=99ll sell=
 them to you for 106.125, I=E2=80=99m barely making any money but you=E2=80=
=99re a good customer so I=E2=80=99ll do you a favor,=E2=80=9D and the cust=
omer says =E2=80=9Cdone=E2=80=9D and pays you 106.125, and actually you pai=
d 101=C2=A0for them and made a huge profit, is that fraud? Well, federal pr=
osecutors sure seemed to think so, and they charged a bunch of bond traders=
 with fraud for doing this.=C2=A0And they got some juries to convict these =
traders, on the fairly straightforward theory that the traders lied to the =
customers. And then the traders appealed, saying =E2=80=9Cno no no you don=
=E2=80=99t understand, the customers were expecting us to lie to them, they=
 lie to us all the time, this is just a market where everyone lies to each =
other, and we all know and accept that, so no one was defrauded.=E2=80=9D A=
nd appeals courts largely  accepted these  arguments, and some of the convi=
ctions were  overturned.[2]=C2=A0You can tell a lawyerly story about this: =
You can use words like =E2=80=9Creasonable reliance=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cm=
ateriality=E2=80=9D to capture the basic notion that, if you lie to people =
who expect you to lie to them, you are not really defrauding them. This sto=
ry will not appeal very much to most prosecutors, but it does seem to have =
some appeal to some judges. It does not seem to have much appeal to=C2=A0ju=
ries. If you say to a jury of normal people =E2=80=9Coh sure I was lying to=
 my customers, but you have to understand, we=E2=80=99re=C2=A0all=C2=A0a bu=
nch of degenerates and we go around lying to each other all day in our mult=
imillion-dollar deals,=E2=80=9D the jury=E2=80=99s reaction might be =E2=80=
=9Cwell then we should put you all in prison.=E2=80=9DThen there are tech s=
tartups.=C2=A0One theory is: If you run a startup, and you are raising mone=
y from investors, and you go to those investors and say things like =E2=80=
=9Cwe had $10 million of revenue last quarter=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe built=
 an electric truck that moves on its own=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe have a fin=
ger-prick blood test that can catch 100 diseases,=E2=80=9D and the investor=
s are like =E2=80=9Cwow=E2=80=9D and give you money, and you were lying, th=
en that is fraud. This theory is very, very, very well supported. It is wha=
t the law actually says, for one thing. (=E2=80=9CIt shall be unlawful for =
any person =E2=80=A6=C2=A0to make any untrue statement of a material fact =
=E2=80=A6=C2=A0in connection with the purchase or sale of any security,=E2=
=80=9D says the law.[3]) Also it is consistent with normal intuitive unders=
tandings of =E2=80=9Cfraud.=E2=80=9D If you just went to a bunch of ordinar=
y people =E2=80=94=C2=A0people who might be on a jury =E2=80=94=C2=A0and as=
ked =E2=80=9Cif I lie to investors to raise money, is that fraud,=E2=80=9D =
they=E2=80=99ll mostly say yes.But another theory is: No, those investors r=
eally want to be lied to. Those investors are holding a competition of the =
form =E2=80=9Cwho can sound the most excited and persuasive and crazy when =
they lie to us,=E2=80=9D and they give their money to the winner. They woul=
dn=E2=80=99t put it quite that way. But what the investors want is a fantas=
ist, a wild-eyed dreamer, a visionary who sees the world not as it is but a=
s it could be. They want someone who looks at  $1 million in revenue and se=
es $10 million. They want someone who looks at some blueprints for an  elec=
tric truck and sees hundreds rolling off the production line. They want som=
eone who looks at a finger-prick blood test that doesn=E2=80=99t work and s=
ees one that does work. They want someone who believes in something that no=
body else believes in, an out-of-consensus visionary who wants to change th=
e world. Obviously obviously obviously they would prefer it if this person=
=E2=80=99s wild belief comes true, if she succeeds in changing the world. B=
ut the first step is to back founders with crazy ideas. And then if one of =
them works out, that pays for 10 that are just crazy.This theory is also we=
ll supported! Lots of venture capitalists will say it out loud! But also, l=
ike, man, look at the entire history of SoftBank Group Corp. Look at how So=
ftBank=E2=80=99s Masayoshi Son met WeWork=E2=80=99s Adam Neumann, and Neuma=
nn pitched him on some vision of office-space-rental changing the world, an=
d Son gave Neumann $3.1 billion. And, famously, =E2=80=9CMr. Neumann has to=
ld others that Mr. Son appreciated how he was crazy=E2=80=94but thought tha=
t he needed to be crazier.=E2=80=9D You don=E2=80=99t say that and then tur=
n around and check every line of the financial projections for exaggeration=
s and unjustified assumptions. If you invest in startups by (1) meeting cra=
zy people and (2) telling them to be crazier, your main investment criterio=
n is not scrupulous accuracy.=C2=A0The problem is that prosecutors don=E2=
=80=99t want to hear this. =E2=80=9CNo no no=C2=A0you don=E2=80=99t underst=
and, these investors were looking for someone to say crazy stuff to them, s=
o I did. It didn=E2=80=99t work out, but they knew going in that the odds o=
f it working out were low. And sure I said that our product already worked,=
 and it didn=E2=80=99t, but that=E2=80=99s just the sort of patter they exp=
ect from a visionary tech founder; they didn=E2=80=99t take that too seriou=
sly.=E2=80=9D That might all be sort of true, but a prosecutor is going to =
be like =E2=80=9Cbut you sold securities by lying about material facts, no?=
=E2=80=9DAnyway:After four years, repeated delays and the birth of her baby=
, Elizabeth Holmes, the founder of the blood testing start-up Theranos, is =
set to stand trial for fraud, capping a saga of Silicon Valley hubris, ambi=
tion and deception.Jury selection begins on Tuesday in federal court in San=
 Jose, Calif., followed by opening arguments next week. Ms. Holmes, whose t=
rial is expected to last three to four months, is battling 12 counts of fra=
ud and conspiracy to commit wire fraud over false claims she made about The=
ranos=E2=80=99s blood tests and business.In 2018, the Department of Justice=
 indicted both her and her business partner and onetime boyfriend, Ramesh B=
alwani, known as Sunny, with the charges. Mr. Balwani=E2=80=99s trial will =
begin early next year. Both have pleaded not guilty.Ms. Holmes=E2=80=99s ca=
se has been held up as a parable of Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s swashbuckling =
=E2=80=9Cfake it till you make it=E2=80=9D culture, which has helped propel=
 the region=E2=80=99s start-ups to unfathomable riches and economic power. =
That same spirit has also allowed grifters and unethical hustlers to flouri=
sh, often with little consequence, raising questions about Silicon Valley=
=E2=80=99s tightening grip on society.Another problem with this defense is =
that I suspect that juries also don=E2=80=99t want to hear it, though I sup=
pose it depends on the jury. If fraud depends on local social expectations,=
 you want a jury that is in on those expectations. If you are a tech founde=
r and get a true jury of your peers =E2=80=94=C2=A0a jury of tech founders =
and venture capitalists =E2=80=94=C2=A0I guess it=E2=80=99s fine?  I mean:L=
egal experts say what Holmes needs are jurors well-versed in the startup sc=
ene who will be open to the idea that the blood-testing company was an inno=
cent failure rather than a massive fraud.=C2=A0According to this view, Holm=
es may be able to prevail if her account of the collapse of Theranos resona=
tes with jurors=E2=80=99 understanding of how entrepreneurs make sales pitc=
hes to attract investors -- and how best-laid plans can go awry.Sure, why n=
ot. If those bond traders had gotten juries of bond traders they probably w=
ould have been acquitted.One more problem with this defense, for Holmes, is=
 that she was pitching blood-testing technology that apparently didn=E2=80=
=99t work. This allowed her to raise a lot of money from investors, but als=
o Theranos  did a lot of blood tests? That didn=E2=80=99t work? And patient=
s who got bad blood-test results will be allowed to testify at her trial? (=
A trial about whether she lied to investors!) Even if the jury is like =E2=
=80=9Cwell sure she lied to investors but they were cool with that, they li=
ke to be lied to, no fraud,=E2=80=9D it is harder to conclude that about th=
e patients. If you go in for a blood test you expect it to work! You didn=
=E2=80=99t sign up for =E2=80=9CSilicon Valley=E2=80=99s swashbuckling =E2=
=80=98fake it till you make it=E2=80=99 culture.=E2=80=9D Venture capitalis=
ts backing a founder want a high-variance lottery ticket. People getting a =
blood test want a low-variance blood test.


