Here=E2=80=99s a weird little Securities and Exchange Commission enforcemen=
t action against a municipal-bond broker-dealer for front-running a client.=
 There=E2=80=99s an Arkansas-based broker named Crews & Associates, run by =
a chief executive officer named Rush Harding, and it advises municipalities=
 on issuing and buying back bonds. One of its clients was the county commis=
sion of Ohio County, West Virginia. The county had some expensive bonds out=
standing, and Crews advised it to tender to buy back those bonds to reduce =
its interest expense. It did this, and reduced its interest expense, and wa=
s presumably happy. But Crews =E2=80=94=C2=A0both before and after it advis=
ed the county to buy back the bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0had been buying the bond=
s for its own account and for its customers; when the county bought back th=
e bonds, Crews and its customers sold and made a quick and undisclosed prof=
it.[4]The profit was about $60,000, on about $6 million of bonds. Obviously=
 you=E2=80=99re not supposed to do that. In fact there is a rule =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board Rule G-17 =E2=80=94=C2=A0saying=
 that municipal underwriters have to disclose conflicts of interest (like o=
wning the bonds you=E2=80=99re telling the client to tender for) to issuers=
.[5] And Crews actually did that? Sort of?On December 14, 2015, pursuant to=
 MSRB Rule G-17, Crews sent the County a letter which documented the relati=
onship between Crews and the County in connection with the proposed tender =
offer. In the letter, Crews acknowledged its obligation as a broker-dealer =
under MSRB Rule G-17 to deal fairly at all times with the County. The lette=
r stated, among other things, that Crews or its respective affiliates may a=
t any time hold long or short positions in the 2006A Bonds and, through emp=
loyees who do not have access to non-public information relating to the 200=
6A Bonds, may trade or otherwise effect transactions in the 2006A Bonds. Th=
e letter also stated that Crews was =E2=80=9Cacting for its own interests=
=E2=80=9D and had =E2=80=9Cfinancial and other interests that differ[ed] fr=
om those of [the County].=E2=80=9D Crews represented that it had =E2=80=9Cn=
ot identified any additional=C2=A0potential or actual material conflicts th=
at require[d] disclosure,=E2=80=9D and that it would notify the County =E2=
=80=9Cif additional potential or actual material conflicts are identified=
=E2=80=9D in the future. Crews did not disclose, in the letter or elsewhere=
, that it had, in fact, already acquired $2.5 million of the 2006A Bonds fo=
r its Affiliate, or that its Affiliate had a financial interest in the tend=
er offer. =E2=80=A6Although its G-17 letter stated Crews and its affiliates=
 =E2=80=9Cmay=E2=80=9D trade in and be long the 2006A bonds, Crews did not =
disclose to the County that it and its Affiliate had, in fact, acquired the=
 2006A Bonds. The County was unaware that Crews was purchasing 2006A Bonds =
from third parties and from Crews customers in the open market and at marke=
t prices and then selling them to the Affiliate. The County did not know th=
at Crews and the Affiliate profited from these transactions.You can sort of=
 see the thinking here. Crews buys some bonds. It sends the issuer a letter=
 saying =E2=80=9Cwe are advising you to buy these bonds, but we need to dis=
close to you that we might be long or short the bonds.=E2=80=9D It thinks, =
well, we=E2=80=99re covered then, we=E2=80=99ve told them that we might own=
 the bonds they=E2=80=99re=C2=A0buying, and that we=E2=80=99re acting for o=
ur own interests; they=E2=80=99re on notice that we might be on the other s=
ide of the trade and making a profit. But the county officials read that le=
tter and are like =E2=80=9Cmeh here=E2=80=99s some boilerplate, whatever, t=
hese are our trusted advisers.=E2=80=9D Crews has arguably technically disc=
losed its conflict of interest, but the SEC thinks that=E2=80=99s not good =
enough; instead of =E2=80=9Cwe may be long or short these bonds=E2=80=9D it=
 needs to say, like, =E2=80=9Cwe have bought $_____ million of these bonds =
for our customers and affiliates at prices of _____, we are planning to buy=
 more, and we have obvious incentives to get you to overpay.=E2=80=9DWe tal=
ked last week about another SEC case against Pearson Plc, a company that (1=
) got hacked and (2) put out disclosure saying =E2=80=9Cwe might get hacked=
 and that would be bad.=E2=80=9D There is sort of a traditional lawyerly vi=
ew that disclosing an actual event as a hypothetical is good enough =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that if you get hacked, you can say =E2=80=9Cwe might get hacked=
=E2=80=9D; that if you own a bunch of bonds you=E2=80=99re telling a client=
 to buy, you can say =E2=80=9Cwe may be long or short these bonds=E2=80=9D =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be good enough for the SEC an=
ymore.
