ider because retail flow is segregated this way; if Robinhood sent all of i=
ts orders to the exchange then the spread on the exchange would be like $58=
.12/$58.13 and everyone would be better off.=E2=80=9D Maybe! I dunno!=C2=A0=
[2] I should say that, in my experience (and inbox), a lot of bond traders =
seem to agree with this characterization of the bond market, and a lot of b=
ond traders seem to vehemently disagree. In general I do not think that the=
 bond market is like a poker game in that, if someone lies to you about the=
 price they paid, and you overpay and then find out, you probably *won=E2=
=80=99t* be like =E2=80=9Cgood one, you got me, well played.=E2=80=9D You=
=E2=80=99ll probably be mad, and yell at them, and maybe refuse to trade wi=
th them for a while. But a lot of bond traders will nonetheless think that =
this is a (rude but acceptable) part of the game, and won=E2=80=99t, like, =
*call the police* about it.[3] Technically that=E2=80=99s a Securities and =
Exchange Commission rule implementing the law, Section 10(b) of the Securit=
ies Exchange Act of 1934.[4] Presumably at the expense of the county: If Cr=
ews hadn=E2=80=99t been buying up the bonds, the holders might have tendere=
d to the county at a lower price.=C2=A0[5] Actually the rule says only that=
 =E2=80=9CIn the conduct of its municipal securities or municipal advisory =
activities, each broker, dealer, municipal securities dealer, and municipal=
 advisor shall deal fairly with all persons and shall not engage in any dec=
eptive, dishonest, or unfair practice.=E2=80=9D But the interpretive guidan=
ce to the rule describes a list of conflicts that need to be disclosed in o=
rder to satisfy the rule.
