<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">PFOF ban?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What if the U.S. Securities and Exchan=
ge Commission bans payment for order flow? Robinhood Markets Inc. gets abou=
t 80% of its revenue from payment for order flow, selling its customers=E2=
=80=99 orders to market makers like Citadel Securities to execute them. Thi=
s is controversial for reasons we have discussed ad nauseam; you can read a=
bout it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24908435.2=
59295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtM=
DcvdGhlLWlwby1tYXJrZXQtd2FzLXRvby1nb29k/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7d3e399a" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here</a> =
and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24908435.25929=
5/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvc=
m9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2EtcHJlc3N1cmVzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc128bba3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;"> here</a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/24908435.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcG=
luaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDctMDgvc29tZW9uZS1pcy1nb2luZy10by1kcmlsbC10aGUtb=
2ls/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB45cfe4b2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: sol=
id; background-color: #ccc;"> here</a>. But the basic point here is that Ro=
binhood doesn=E2=80=99t charge commissions to trade stocks or options or cr=
yptocurrencies, so its customers trade a lot, and it can afford to do that =
because market makers pay for the privilege of trading with its customers. =
If they couldn=E2=80=99t do that, then Robinhood would have to start chargi=
ng commissions, and the whole fun Robinhood thing =E2=80=94=C2=A0the whole =
Robinhood=C2=A0<em>era=C2=A0</em>of excitable retail trading and meme stock=
s and options-driven price moves and so forth =E2=80=94=C2=A0would come to =
an end. Or that=E2=80=99s the worry. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/24908435.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdz=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMzAvcm9iaW5ob29kLWZhbGxzLWFmdGVyLXNlYy1oaW50cy1hdC1=
wYXltZW50LWZvci1vcmRlci1mbG93LWJhbg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe8f1c0fe" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> So</a>:</p><b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood Markets Inc. continued to =
slide in premarket trading after U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission Ch=
airman Gary Gensler said a full ban on payment for order flow is =E2=80=9Co=
n the table.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Robinhood fell about =
3.3% in early trading Tuesday after Gensler told Barron=E2=80=99s the day b=
efore that paying for order flow -- where brokerages send customer orders t=
o trading firms and receive payments in return -- has =E2=80=9Can inherent =
conflict of interest.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gensler has =
previously made similar points about the practice, which has been in Washin=
gton=E2=80=99s crosshairs for months as policy makers scrutinize the mechan=
ics of retail trading in the wake of the run-up in meme stocks like GameSto=
p Corp. Still, any mention of an outright ban can rattle investors in part =
because payment for order flow makes up a significant share of Robinhood=E2=
=80=99s revenue: the company brought in about 80% of its second-quarter rev=
enue from payments for its customers=E2=80=99 stock, options and cryptocurr=
ency transactions.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Brokers like Robinhood p=
rofit by selling trades, prompting some lawmakers to question whether that =
encourages firms to push clients to engage in excessive buying and selling.=
 =C2=A0In the Monday interview with the online news publication, Gensler sa=
id it allows market makers to get a =E2=80=9Cfirst look=E2=80=9D at transac=
tion data that may lead to unfair advantages.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/24908435.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmFycm9ucy5jb20vYW1wL2FydGljbGV=
zL3NlYy1jaGFpcm1hbi1zYXlzLWJhbm5pbmctcGF5bWVudC1mb3Itb3JkZXItaXMtb24tdGhlLX=
RhYmxlLTUxNjMwMzUwNTk1/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB39daa519" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the Barron=E2=80=99s articl=
e</a>. I should say, nobody seems to think that Gensler particularly means =
this, and I don=E2=80=99t want to take it too seriously. I do, however, wan=
t to describe my guess about what will happen if the SEC does in fact ban p=
ayment for order flow. I don=E2=80=99t think the likely outcome is =E2=80=
=9CRobinhood disappears,=E2=80=9D or even =E2=80=9CRobinhood starts chargin=
g commissions.=E2=80=9D Robinhood does not want to charge commissions! It=
=E2=80=99s a bad customer experience! It=E2=80=99s bad for trading volume! =
Surely there is some way around this (entirely hypothetical) ban?=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, sure. It=E2=80=99s simple really. When I=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24908435.259295/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvcm9i=
aW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2EtcHJlc3N1cmVzLXBheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCc128bba3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> explained payment for order flow back in February</a=
>, I started from the notion that a retail broker (like Robinhood) could =
=E2=80=9Cinternalize=E2=80=9D trades. Some Robinhood customers want to buy =
stock, other customers want to sell stock, and Robinhood just pairs them of=
f with each other rather than routing their orders to the stock exchange. T=
he prices on the stock exchange have some spread: Robinhood=E2=80=99s custo=
mers could buy stock at the offer for (say) $58.25, or they could sell it a=
t the bid for (say) $58.00. By pairing them off with each other, Robinhood =
can capture that spread and share it with the customers. Its customers coul=
d buy at $58.15, saving 10 cents; its other customers could sell at $58.10,=
 making an extra 10 cents; and Robinhood itself could charge 5 cents for ma=
king this happen. (These numbers are kind of fake for ease of illustration;=
 the real numbers are often fractions of a penny =E2=80=94=C2=A0and describ=
ed at the end of this section.) Everyone is better off than they would be i=
f the order went to the exchange.[1]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of cou=
rse that=E2=80=99s not actually what happens. It is the rough economic intu=
ition for what happens. But Robinhood doesn=E2=80=99t actually do the match=
ing up of customers. Someone else does, a market maker or internalizer or w=
holesaler or dealer or whatever you want to call it. I wrote:</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In practice a typical retail broker doesn=E2=
=80=99t have the ability to do this, so it sends its orders to what is usua=
lly, in the business, called a =E2=80=9Cwholesaler=E2=80=9D (or sometimes =
=E2=80=9Cinternalizer=E2=80=9D), and usually, outside of the business, call=
ed a =E2=80=9Chigh-frequency trader.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Popular wholesalers incl=
ude Citadel Securities, G1X Execution Services LLC, Two Sigma Securities LL=
C, Virtu Financial Inc., Wolverine Securities, etc. The wholesaler does the=
 thing I just said: It pays the sellers more for their shares than the exch=
ange offers, charges the buyers less for shares than the exchange would, an=
d keeps 5 cents for itself. Well, it keeps, say, 3 cents for itself, and se=
nds 2 cents back to the retail broker who sent it the trade. The broker has=
 subcontracted the internalizing job to the wholesaler, and they share the =
profits.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The 2 cents it sends =
back to the broker (in my fake hypothetical numbers) is called =E2=80=9Cpay=
ment for order flow.=E2=80=9D The 10 cents that customers save (again, in m=
y fake numbers) is called =E2=80=9Cprice improvement.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I hope the solution is obvious? If Robinhood can=E2=80=
=99t get payment for order flow =E2=80=94=C2=A0if it can=E2=80=99t subcontr=
act this internalizing function to a market maker =E2=80=94=C2=A0then it ca=
n just do it in-house. It can use its balance sheet to internalize customer=
 trades, executing those trades at better prices than are available on the =
public exchange (and so satisfying its best-execution obligations), and col=
lecting a spread for itself instead of sharing that spread with Citadel Sec=
urities or whoever. Instead of like =E2=80=9CRobinhood routes your order to=
 Citadel Securities and Citadel Securities executes the order, makes a prof=
it=C2=A0and pays some of it to Robinhood,=E2=80=9D it will be like =E2=80=
=9CRobinhood routes your order to Robinhood and Robinhood executes the orde=
r, makes a profit and keeps it.=E2=80=9D The payment-for-order-flow complex=
 is sort of collapsed and streamlined. But it's the same trade, with the sa=
me basic economics.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And of course Robinhood=
=C2=A0<em>makes=C2=A0</em><em>money=C2=A0</em>doing this =E2=80=94=C2=A0it =
captures the public-market spread, gives some of it to customers, and keeps=
 the rest for itself =E2=80=94=C2=A0which can allow it to continue offering=
 zero-commission trades.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to make fou=
r points here.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First,=C2=A0<em>Robinhood ha=
s said that it will do this</em>. This is not wild speculation on my part. =
During the roadshow for Robinhood=E2=80=99s initial public offering last mo=
nth, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24908435.2592=
95/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZm94YnVzaW5lc3MuY29tL21hcmtldHMvcm9iaW5ob29kLWlwby10d2lz=
dC1idXNpbmVzcy1tb2RlbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB79fc150a" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Charlie Gasparino reported<=
/a> that Robinhood was telling investors that it was thinking about getting=
 into the market making business. I was a little skeptical that this was a =
good idea; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2490843=
5.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMD=
ctMjkvYXJjaGVnb3Mtd2FzLXRvby1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBbbf55d3b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> I wrote at the time</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Robinhood could take on a lot of balance-sheet risk in all the stocks it=
 offers, and build the sophisticated speedy technology to accurately and ra=
pidly price and trade those stocks and lay off risk on public exchanges? An=
d make even more money than it gets paid for order flow? I mean, people do =
it; there are huge important high-frequency trading firms started by young =
people in recent decades, it is not impossible or anything. And yet when I =
think of Robinhood, well-capitalized prudent risk management, careful regul=
atory compliance and 100% reliable technology are not the first things I th=
ink of.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the regulator=
y status quo it probably makes more sense for Robinhood to concentrate on u=
ser experience and marketing, and subcontract the risky internalizing to pr=
ofessionals. In a world in which payment for order flow is banned, that opt=
ion is off the table, and Robinhood=E2=80=99s best move might be to do the =
internalizing itself. It=E2=80=99s not a trivial business, but it=E2=80=99s=
 a business that a lot of people do, and presumably Robinhood =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0with its brand name and huge and lucrative customer base =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
could hire someone to do it.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, <em>pa=
yment for order flow is prohibited in some other countries, and this seems =
to be how=C2=A0commission-free trading works there</em>.=C2=A0For instance =
eToro Group Ltd. is=C2=A0an Israeli company <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/24908435.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucmV1dGVycy5jb20vY=
