<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Muni front-running</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a weird little Securiti=
es and Exchange Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/24908435.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2=
UvMjAyMS0xNjY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6d815e36" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">enforcement action</a> against a mun=
icipal-bond broker-dealer for front-running a client. There=E2=80=99s an Ar=
kansas-based broker named Crews &amp; Associates, run by a chief executive =
officer named Rush Harding, and it advises municipalities on issuing and bu=
ying back bonds. One of its clients was the county commission of Ohio Count=
y, West Virginia. The county had some expensive bonds outstanding, and Crew=
s advised it to tender to buy back those bonds to reduce its interest expen=
se. It did this, and reduced its interest expense, and was presumably happy=
. But Crews =E2=80=94=C2=A0both before and after it advised the county to b=
uy back the bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0had been buying the bonds for its own acco=
unt and for its customers; when the county bought back the bonds, Crews and=
 its customers sold and made a quick and undisclosed profit.[4]</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The profit was about $60,000, on about $6 million of b=
onds. Obviously you=E2=80=99re not supposed to do that. In fact there is a =
rule =E2=80=94=C2=A0Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board Rule G-17 =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0saying that municipal underwriters have to disclose conflicts of i=
nterest (like owning the bonds you=E2=80=99re telling the client to tender =
for) to issuers.[5] And Crews <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/24908435.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWl=
uLzIwMjEvMzQtOTI3NjgucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5e73d32d" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">actually did that</a>? S=
ort of?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On December 14, 2015, p=
ursuant to MSRB Rule G-17, Crews sent the County a letter which documented =
the relationship between Crews and the County in connection with the propos=
ed tender offer. In the letter, Crews acknowledged its obligation as a brok=
er-dealer under MSRB Rule G-17 to deal fairly at all times with the County.=
 The letter stated, among other things, that Crews or its respective affili=
ates may at any time hold long or short positions in the 2006A Bonds and, t=
hrough employees who do not have access to non-public information relating =
to the 2006A Bonds, may trade or otherwise effect transactions in the 2006A=
 Bonds. The letter also stated that Crews was =E2=80=9Cacting for its own i=
nterests=E2=80=9D and had =E2=80=9Cfinancial and other interests that diffe=
r[ed] from those of [the County].=E2=80=9D Crews represented that it had =
=E2=80=9Cnot identified any additional=C2=A0potential or actual material co=
nflicts that require[d] disclosure,=E2=80=9D and that it would notify the C=
ounty =E2=80=9Cif additional potential or actual material conflicts are ide=
ntified=E2=80=9D in the future. Crews did not disclose, in the letter or el=
sewhere, that it had, in fact, already acquired $2.5 million of the 2006A B=
onds for its Affiliate, or that its Affiliate had a financial interest in t=
he tender offer. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Although its G-1=
7 letter stated Crews and its affiliates =E2=80=9Cmay=E2=80=9D trade in and=
 be long the 2006A bonds, Crews did not disclose to the County that it and =
its Affiliate had, in fact, acquired the 2006A Bonds. The County was unawar=
e that Crews was purchasing 2006A Bonds from third parties and from Crews c=
ustomers in the open market and at market prices and then selling them to t=
he Affiliate. The County did not know that Crews and the Affiliate profited=
 from these transactions.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You =
can sort of see the thinking here. Crews buys some bonds. It sends the issu=
er a letter saying =E2=80=9Cwe are advising you to buy these bonds, but we =
need to disclose to you that we might be long or short the bonds.=E2=80=9D =
It thinks, well, we=E2=80=99re covered then, we=E2=80=99ve told them that w=
e might own the bonds they=E2=80=99re=C2=A0buying, and that we=E2=80=99re a=
cting for our own interests; they=E2=80=99re on notice that we might be on =
the other side of the trade and making a profit. But the county officials r=
ead that letter and are like =E2=80=9Cmeh here=E2=80=99s some boilerplate, =
whatever, these are our trusted advisers.=E2=80=9D Crews has arguably techn=
ically disclosed its conflict of interest, but the SEC thinks that=E2=80=99=
s not good enough; instead of =E2=80=9Cwe may be long or short these bonds=
=E2=80=9D it needs to say, like, =E2=80=9Cwe have bought $_____ million of =
these bonds for our customers and affiliates at prices of _____, we are pla=
nning to buy more, and we have obvious incentives to get you to overpay.=E2=
=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/24908435.259295/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMjQvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtd2FudC10by1zdGF5LXBvcH=
VsYXI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeb4a5b35" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">talked last week</a> about another SEC cas=
e against Pearson Plc, a company that (1) got hacked and (2) put out disclo=
sure saying =E2=80=9Cwe might get hacked and that would be bad.=E2=80=9D Th=
ere is sort of a traditional lawyerly view that disclosing an actual event =
as a hypothetical is good enough =E2=80=94=C2=A0that if you get hacked, you=
 can say =E2=80=9Cwe might get hacked=E2=80=9D; that if you own a bunch of =
bonds you=E2=80=99re telling a client to buy, you can say =E2=80=9Cwe may b=
e long or short these bonds=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it doesn=E2=80=99t =
seem to be good enough for the SEC anymore.</p><table class=3D"header" widt=
h=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
